                    <h1>Tags</h1>
                    <p>The Office of the Historian’s “Subject Taxonomy of the History of U.S.
                        Foreign Relations” covers <span data-template="tags:tag-count"/> subjects,
                        organized into three major sections: <a href="$app/tags/people">People</a>,
                            <a href="$app/tags/places">Places</a>, and <a href="$app/tags/topics"
                            >Topics</a>. Drill into one of these sections, or view <a
                            href="$app/tags/all">the full taxonomy</a>.</p>
                    <p>The taxonomy has been applied to a small but growing segment of the resources
                        on the Office of the Historian’s website: <span
                            data-template="tags:count-resources"
                            data-template-collection="secretary-bios"/>
                        <a href="$app/departmenthistory/people/secretaries"> biographies of the
                            Secretaries of State</a> and <span data-template="tags:count-resources"
                            data-template-collection="frus"/> volumes from the <a
                            href="$app/historicaldocuments">
                            <em>Foreign Relations of the United States</em>
                        </a> series.</p>
                    <p>With <span data-template="tags:count-resource-tags"/> tags applied to date,
                        this growing resource exposes connections across the accumulated knowledge
                        of the Office of the Historian.</p>
